---
import { buildMobileData, taxRatesData } from "../../data/charts";
import BarChart from "../charts/BarChart.astro";
import DonutChart from "../charts/DonutChart.astro";

const mobileData = buildMobileData();
---

<section id="tax" aria-labelledby="tax-heading">
	<div class="two-col tax-layout">
		<div class="col-charts">
			<figure class="chart-box reveal">
				<figcaption class="chart-title">Where Corporate Profits Are Shifted</figcaption>
				<div id="tax-donut-desktop-chart" class="desktop-chart" role="img" aria-label="Donut chart showing where corporate profits are shifted: UK Dependencies 23%, Netherlands 22%, Bermuda 18%, Ireland 12%, Luxembourg 15%, Other 10%">
					<DonutChart />
				</div>
				<div id="tax-donut-mobile-chart" class="mobile-chart" role="img" aria-label="Bar chart showing where corporate profits are shifted to tax havens">
					<BarChart id="tax-donut-mobile-bars" items={mobileData.donut} />
				</div>
				<table class="sr-only">
					<caption>Where Corporate Profits Are Shifted</caption>
					<thead><tr><th>Destination</th><th>Share</th></tr></thead>
					<tbody>
						<tr><td>UK Dependencies</td><td>23%</td></tr>
						<tr><td>Netherlands</td><td>22%</td></tr>
						<tr><td>Bermuda &amp; Cayman</td><td>18%</td></tr>
						<tr><td>Luxembourg</td><td>15%</td></tr>
						<tr><td>Ireland</td><td>12%</td></tr>
						<tr><td>Other</td><td>10%</td></tr>
					</tbody>
				</table>
			</figure>
			<figure class="chart-box reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.12s">
				<figcaption class="chart-title">Who Really Pays: Effective Tax Rates</figcaption>
				<div role="img" aria-label="Bar chart showing effective tax rates: Richest 400 families pay 23% (all taxes), median household pays 25%, top statutory rate is 37%">
					<BarChart id="tax-rates-chart" items={taxRatesData} />
				</div>
			</figure>
		</div>
		<div class="col-text">
			<div class="section-label reveal-left">Tax Avoidance &amp; Offshore Wealth</div>
			<h2 id="tax-heading" class="reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.1s">
				The Hidden<br />Trillions
			</h2>
			<p>
				The wealth concentration shown above is an undercount. An
				estimated $32+ trillion sits offshore — beyond democratic reach.
				Corporations shift over $1 trillion in profits to tax havens
				annually. The global average corporate statutory tax rate has been
				halved since 1985, from 49% to 23%, in a race to the bottom that
				makes redistribution structurally impossible. The UK's Crown
				Dependencies and Overseas Territories alone are responsible for
				23% of global corporate tax losses.
			</p>
			<p>
				Meanwhile, illicit financial flows strip $88 billion per year from
				Africa — more than the continent receives in aid. The system does
				not merely produce inequality — it actively shields it from
				democratic correction. Tax havens are not rogue actors. They are
				built into the architecture of global capital: the City of London,
				Delaware, the Netherlands.
			</p>
			<div class="pull-quote reveal">
				<blockquote>
					"The tax system has been turned against the very people it is
					supposed to serve. When billionaires pay lower tax rates than
					their secretaries, it is not a loophole — it is the design."
				</blockquote>
				<cite>— Gabriel Zucman, <em>The Hidden Wealth of Nations</em>, 2015</cite>
			</div>
			<div class="stat-grid reveal">
				<div class="stat-box" role="group" aria-labelledby="stat-label-tax-0">
					<div class="num" data-target="32" data-prefix="$" data-suffix="T">$0T</div>
					<div class="label" id="stat-label-tax-0">
						Estimated global offshore wealth (2012 estimate, Tax Justice Network)<button type="button" class="cite-ref" aria-label="View source: Tax Justice Network 2012" aria-expanded="false" data-source="Tax Justice Network, The Price of Offshore Revisited, 2012" data-url="https://taxjustice.net/reports/the-price-of-offshore-revisited/">*</button>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="stat-box" role="group" aria-labelledby="stat-label-tax-1">
					<div class="num" data-target="1" data-prefix="$" data-suffix="T">$0T</div>
					<div class="label" id="stat-label-tax-1">In corporate profits shifted to tax havens annually</div>
				</div>
				<div class="stat-box" role="group" aria-labelledby="stat-label-tax-2">
					<div class="num" data-target="23" data-prefix="" data-suffix="%">0%</div>
					<div class="label" id="stat-label-tax-2">
						Effective tax rate paid by the richest 400 US families (all taxes, Saez &amp; Zucman 2019)<button type="button" class="cite-ref" aria-label="View source: Saez &amp; Zucman 2019" aria-expanded="false" data-source="Saez &amp; Zucman, The Triumph of Injustice, 2019" data-url="https://gabriel-zucman.eu/uktaxes/">*</button>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="stat-box" role="group" aria-labelledby="stat-label-tax-3">
					<div class="num" data-target="88" data-prefix="$" data-suffix="B">$0B</div>
					<div class="label" id="stat-label-tax-3">
						Annual illicit financial flows from Africa — more than total aid received (UNCTAD 2020)<button type="button" class="cite-ref" aria-label="View source: UNCTAD 2020" aria-expanded="false" data-source="UNCTAD, Economic Development in Africa Report, 2020" data-url="https://unctad.org/publication/economic-development-africa-report-2020">*</button>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<p class="source">
				Source:
				<a href="https://taxjustice.net/reports/the-state-of-tax-justice-2024/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Tax Justice Network State of Tax Justice 2024</a> · Saez &amp; Zucman ·
				<a href="https://unctad.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">UNCTAD</a> ·
				<a href="https://gfintegrity.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Global Financial Integrity</a>
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>
	<aside class="global-south-callout reveal" aria-label="On the Race to the Bottom">
		<h3>On the Race to the Bottom</h3>
		<p>
			States compete to attract capital by gutting their own tax bases.
			Ireland's 12.5% corporate rate drew multinationals away from
			neighbours. The Netherlands became a conduit for profit shifting on
			an industrial scale. Delaware offers corporate anonymity rivalling
			any Caribbean island. The result is a global architecture of tax
			competition that systematically defunds the public institutions
			needed to counteract inequality.
		</p>
		<p>
			The 2021 global minimum tax agreement — set at just 15% — was hailed
			as historic. But it was designed with enough carve-outs to preserve
			the system it claimed to reform. A 15% floor does not end the race
			to the bottom — it merely sets a new basement. The democratic
			capacity to fund universal services, cancel debt, or finance a green
			transition is being dismantled one tax cut at a time.
		</p>
	</aside>
</section>
